Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Notes About Atomic Units", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811943087324304*^9, 3.811943093631875*^9}, {
  3.8119431254812403`*^9, 
  3.8119431265950055`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b6c1bc87-ae5d-5d41-8077-\
1b482d96642f"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["What Are Atomic Units?", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8119431219003825`*^9, 
  3.8119431344722147`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e500752b-58c1-c541-885c-\
a8b485d4e138"],

Cell["\<\
Up to this point in the class, we have stuck pretty consistently with the use \
of SI units for all of our calculations, demonstrations, and exercises. \
However, we\[CloseCurlyQuote]ve seen that sometimes these units leave us with \
many, many constants in our answers. For example, we saw that the \
ground-state energy of the hydrogen atom is written\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8119430974005985`*^9, 
  3.811943194502799*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2606055d-d947-2f41-aaf9-\
84d1c80b4f79"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["E",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["H",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], 
    StyleBox[
     RowBox[{"1", "s"}],
     FontSlant->"Italic"]]], "=", 
  RowBox[{"-", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["m", "e"], 
     SuperscriptBox[
      StyleBox["e",
       FontSlant->"Italic"], "4"]}], 
    RowBox[{"32", 
     SuperscriptBox["\[Pi]", "2"], 
     SubscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "0"], 
     SuperscriptBox["\[HBar]", "2"]}]]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811939159903883*^9, 3.8119392103826303`*^9}, {
  3.8119393358094797`*^9, 3.8119393592738667`*^9}, {3.811939516691291*^9, 
  3.8119395296122313`*^9}, {3.8119395681458282`*^9, 3.8119395710471015`*^9}, {
  3.8119396323397303`*^9, 3.811939640127038*^9}, {3.8119396974949074`*^9, 
  3.8119397255363784`*^9}, {3.8119417277677493`*^9, 3.811941772989243*^9}, {
  3.811941819461093*^9, 3.811941883219368*^9}, {3.811943230943274*^9, 
  3.8119432564451942`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"29700b23-5ecf-1f42-a081-\
e26b596fc4bf"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "But we have already seen that many of our answers in the case of atoms have \
been yielding multiples of a certain values. In fact, we\[CloseCurlyQuote]ve \
already been using the Bohr radius, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["a", "0"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5d795bfb-cc0a-d34e-91d2-aa6370392214"],
 ", as a means to simplify our input and output when discussing the radial \
dependence of hydrogen atomic wavefunctions."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811943271287572*^9, 
  3.8119433873831987`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a6ba1edb-39c6-f345-afa4-\
eb1679de4d0c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Atomic units are simply a set of such collections of constants that \
simplify our equations and our answers when working with calculations of \
atoms and molecules. For example, the atomic unit of energy is the Hartree, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["E", "h"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "754e6cef-c86b-f945-a84f-f9088fd1d837"],
 ","
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811943399050423*^9, 
  3.811943515046967*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"333407d4-4e74-6743-a865-\
40471fcfc765"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["E", "h"],
   TraditionalForm], "=", 
  FractionBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["m", "e"], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "4"]}], 
   RowBox[{"16", 
    SuperscriptBox["\[Pi]", "2"], 
    SubscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "0"], 
    SuperscriptBox["\[HBar]", "2"]}]]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811939159903883*^9, 3.8119392103826303`*^9}, {
  3.8119393358094797`*^9, 3.8119393592738667`*^9}, {3.811939516691291*^9, 
  3.8119395296122313`*^9}, {3.8119395681458282`*^9, 3.8119395710471015`*^9}, {
  3.8119396323397303`*^9, 3.811939640127038*^9}, {3.8119396974949074`*^9, 
  3.8119397255363784`*^9}, {3.8119417277677493`*^9, 3.811941772989243*^9}, {
  3.811941819461093*^9, 3.811941883219368*^9}, {3.811943230943274*^9, 
  3.8119432564451942`*^9}, {3.811943534108714*^9, 
  3.811943539770031*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"4780f0e7-7e6f-474b-9ed0-\
54485ba67fce"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Using this unit, we see that the ground-state energy of the hydrogen atom \
is just \[Minus]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["E", "h"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5bb9caa0-79e1-b74d-8e7e-e156c183d523"],
 "/2, or \[Minus]0.5 Hartrees. A list of such units is given in the table \
below. Essentially all software for performing computational chemistry \
utilizes atomic units in its output."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8119435441081405`*^9, 3.8119436350896797`*^9}, 
   3.936180577011118*^9},ExpressionUUID->"50e714eb-e594-4f48-ae01-\
8941e113805b"],

