}], "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8119485958262997`*^9, 3.811948775665064*^9}, {
  3.8119488423782682`*^9, 
  3.811948905983163*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a98473cd-c78d-46f5-b73f-\
ea651a4096db"],

Cell["\<\
This approach can in general be extended to atoms with even more electrons or \
even molecules. Essentially all computational chemistry calculations begin \
with solving a Hamiltonian through a self-consistent field method.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811949197439953*^9, 3.8119492016952276`*^9}, {
  3.811949250570031*^9, 3.8119493308408375`*^9}, {3.8121204959998856`*^9, 
  3.812120496930242*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1b445155-8713-4f18-bef0-\
e2585ce1d1e8"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "There is a limit to the accuracy of the Hartree method (and the \
Hartree-Fock method, which we will come to in a moment). Because the method \
assumes that each electron experiences only the average potential created by \
the other electrons, ",
 StyleBox["any correlation between the electrons is not accounted for in the \
method",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". Therefore, we can call the difference between the true energy and the \
Hartree energy the correlation energy of the system. For helium, the \
correlation energy (which also tells you about the accuracy of the method) is "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8119493328653364`*^9, 
  3.811949554362116*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9897ef40-8132-433b-bba0-\
7be2ed3c160e"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  StyleBox["CE",
   FontSlant->"Italic"], "=", 
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["E",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "exact"], "-", 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["E",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "Hartree"]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.810112811439228*^9, 3.8101128248442793`*^9}, {
   3.810479494926491*^9, 3.8104795038498344`*^9}, {3.810479572543576*^9, 
