Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Fermions and Pauli Exclusion", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8126220217605495`*^9, 
  3.8126220467996254`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"72401e31-f0c0-49d6-97d9-\
c662fef2a2e9"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s highlight two important conclusions from the \
exercise above. First, we see that bosons must be in a ",
 StyleBox["symmetric",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " configuration of the wavefunction, meaning that they can (although the don\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]t have to) occupy the same state at the same time. Because \
bosons can occupy the same state, they are subject to unique phenomena at low \
temperatures, most notably Bose-Einstein condensation. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8126217820187893`*^9, 3.8126219113856688`*^9}, {
  3.812622035720984*^9, 3.8126220410509644`*^9}, {3.8126224402183876`*^9, 
  3.8126225145516453`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"896bfffd-f011-4b6a-8357-\
4b779a561642"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The second conclusion is generally more relevant for chemists, as it \
involves the allowed states of fermions such as the electron. Note that ",
 StyleBox["we have just concluded that electrons with the same spatial \
wavefunction ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 StyleBox["cannot",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 StyleBox[" be in the same spin state",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". This statement is in fact just a different wording of the familiar Pauli \
exclusion principle!"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8126219138758383`*^9, 3.8126220118342495`*^9}, {
  3.812622054255213*^9, 3.8126220573764324`*^9}, {3.8126226257791166`*^9, 
  3.8126227365687103`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8012577c-8817-4b10-a4e1-\
07c21bae7019"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The Pauli exclusion principle is normally stated as follows: no two \
electrons in an atom can have the same values of the four quantum numbers ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox["l",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["m", "l"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "30debe00-c44a-403c-a0f6-f39402b79e55"],
 ", and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["m", "s"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "6ecdec53-8056-446c-adb3-8850ebfe5c41"],
 ". If ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox["l",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["m", "l"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "e765d593-8a12-43ca-8ccd-b8463c3db27e"],
 " are the same (meaning the spatial wavefunctions are the same), then ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["m", "s"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "1e3db7aa-b750-4311-83bd-ec7f41cd0ece"],
 " (which specifies electron spin, remember), must be different, which is \
exactly what we have concluded above."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.812622741201082*^9, 3.812623014204894*^9}, {
  3.9177031140095143`*^9, 
  3.9177031227231455`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e00e954c-591c-4307-b5ec-\
803dd7038a9d"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
Hartree-Fock Theory, Antisymmetric Wavefunctions, and Slater Determinants\
\>", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8126230614048557`*^9, 
  3.8126230779991884`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8c199215-ab84-4310-8d8a-\
1c23a228bfc8"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The Helium Atom and the Hartree-Fock Approximation", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8126279521967125`*^9, 
  3.812627959307138*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f6de1344-42bd-4ee4-bb3a-\
00d0c277e392"],

Cell["\<\
We already discussed the Hartree approximation and how we could use it to \
find the approximate energy and wavefunction of a helium atom. Remember that \
we represented the wavefunction of our system as the product of two \
one-electron orbitals,\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8126279642221684`*^9, 
  3.812628022174715*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ff7b21d2-081e-4dde-bd43-\
d36ba561dfe4"],

