Cell[TextData[{
 "for the eigenvector matrix ",
 StyleBox["C",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " and the diagonal eigenvalue matrix \[Epsilon]. This equation is known as \
the Roothan equation. If you read the output from computational chemistry \
code, it may say something like \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]diagonalizing Fock \
matrix\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote], which means it is solving the Roothan \
equations for the eigenvectors and eigenvalues. This solution must be found \
iteratively through the SCF method."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8127121854958644`*^9, 
  3.8127122759267693`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b3d03f11-5dc0-4e95-b07b-\
066576bbf768"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
The Hartree-Fock Method Represents the Starting Point for Computational \
Chemistry\
\>", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.812712288476062*^9, 
  3.812712315092065*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ed7897a7-318b-4dae-a7ac-\
c284cda11223"],

Cell["\<\
It must be said that Hartree-Fock calculations are rarely used in modern \
computational chemistry. That\[CloseCurlyQuote]s because they simply aren\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]t sufficiently accurate for most modern research. However, \
the Hartree-Fock method is still extremely important. It remains the starting \
point for almost every type of computational chemistry. For example, M\
\[OSlash]ller\[Dash]Plesset second-order perturbation theory is commonly used \
in computational chemistry, and it functions by finding the second-order \
perturbation corrections to the solutions from the Hartree-Fock Method. In \
addition, density functional theory, perhaps the most widely-used electronic \
structure method, bears a striking resemblance to the Hartree-Fock method, \
although the details are slightly different.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.812712317184681*^9, 
  3.8127125036753197`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"13f014a7-fd1e-4e51-b624-\
4fc09eeba565"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Perturbation Theory", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8119363893128185`*^9, 
  3.8119363920218964`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"78cc580d-d1e3-264e-adde-\
5d6615709ae6"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
Finding Solutions to an Unknown Problem by Small Changes to a Known Problem\
\>", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811936618348875*^9, 
  3.81193668192865*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e5ac5856-700b-d145-88d6-\
f51d3043b11b"],

Cell["\<\
The idea behind perturbation theory is that we can start with a problem that \
we do know how to solve and add new terms that give corrections, or \
perturbations, that account for the differences between the ideal and real \
systems. Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s start again with the time-independent Schr\
\[ODoubleDot]dinger equation for some system,\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811936696078113*^9, 
  3.8119368021870704`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1e54d56c-b794-db43-8f92-\
36e5c0f0258e"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{
       OverscriptBox[
        StyleBox["H",
         FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], "|", "\[Psi]"}], 
      "\[RightAngleBracket]"}], "=", 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["E",
       FontSlant->"Italic"], "|", "\[Psi]"}]}], "\[RightAngleBracket]"}], "                                           ", 
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["H",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], "\[Psi]"}], "=", 
  StyleBox[
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["E",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[Psi]"}]], "  "}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811593312893673*^9, 3.8115933831661987`*^9}, {
  3.811593489620569*^9, 
  3.811593494195689*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"d77eee11-2d43-c34e-b756-\
9b90e6238f16"],

Cell["\<\
If this unknown system resembles some well-characterized system that we have \
solved previously, we can write the Hamiltonian operator in the form\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8119368296846113`*^9, 
  3.811936884966194*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"74afa30f-9530-4f49-b64a-\
455fb3a1911d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  OverscriptBox[
   StyleBox["H",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], "=", 
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["H",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], 
    RowBox[{"(", "0", ")"}]], "+", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["H",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], 
    RowBox[{"(", "1", ")"}]]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811593312893673*^9, 3.8115933831661987`*^9}, {
  3.811593489620569*^9, 3.811593494195689*^9}, {3.811936891449876*^9, 
  3.811936898021762*^9}, {3.8119369660148945`*^9, 
  3.8119369743020782`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3d50ace5-1519-5c4a-9a83-\
20a5189546c8"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["H",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], 
   RowBox[{"(", "0", ")"}]]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.811593312893673*^9, 3.8115933831661987`*^9}, {
   3.811593489620569*^9, 3.811593494195689*^9}, {3.811936891449876*^9, 
   3.811936898021762*^9}, {3.8119369660148945`*^9, 3.8119369743020782`*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"72e428e2-647d-024c-bb3f-6d17ec295345"],
 "is the Hamiltonian operator for our known system that we can solve exactly,"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811936980651084*^9, 
  3.8119370017671366`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c3f4f1ae-d64a-4645-8d46-\
2d3397669c60"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox[
        OverscriptBox[
         StyleBox["H",
          FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], 
        RowBox[{"(", "0", ")"}]], "|", 
       SuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", 
        RowBox[{"(", "0", ")"}]]}], "\[RightAngleBracket]"}], "=", 
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox[
       StyleBox["E",
        FontSlant->"Italic"], 
       RowBox[{"(", "0", ")"}]], "|", 
      SuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", 
       RowBox[{"(", "0", ")"}]]}]}], "\[RightAngleBracket]"}], "                                          ", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["H",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], 
    RowBox[{"(", "0", ")"}]], 
   SuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", 
    RowBox[{"(", "0", ")"}]]}], "=", 
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["E",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], 
    RowBox[{"(", "0", ")"}]], 
   SuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", 
    RowBox[{"(", "0", ")"}]]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811593312893673*^9, 3.8115933831661987`*^9}, {
  3.811593489620569*^9, 3.811593494195689*^9}, {3.811937010282008*^9, 
  3.811937038396288*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e0413f56-0f70-c841-a859-\
fa01a46d3941"],

Cell["\<\
The second term in the Hamiltonian represents the perturbation to the system. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811937052450474*^9, 3.811937207097064*^9}, 
   3.81193754168439*^9},ExpressionUUID->"5b17942f-f698-1942-b474-\
afd041837dd8"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Example: The Anharmonic Oscillator", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811937555787799*^9, 
  3.811937572375161*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"91acf4e2-a85c-d04c-bf80-\
e877800e2fe3"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Remember that we already briefly discussed an example of such a \
perturbation in the context of the harmonic oscillator, where we represented \
the shape of our potential energy function as a Taylor series expansion about \
the minimum energy at ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["r",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["r",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "0"], "=", "0"}]}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.8105567537363048`*^9, 3.810556892278119*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"34e4f4dc-8624-5241-975f-9e2414dafd07"],
 ","
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.811937548639083*^9},ExpressionUUID->"0c4e9de1-1fc3-044a-9757-\
ab70cdd3b6ae"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["V",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    StyleBox["r",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], ")"}]}], "=", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     FractionBox["1", "2"], 
     SuperscriptBox[
      StyleBox["kr",
       FontSlant->"Italic"], "2"]}], "+", 
    RowBox[{
     FractionBox["1", "6"], " ", 
     SuperscriptBox[
      StyleBox[
       RowBox[{"\[Gamma]", 
        StyleBox["r",
         FontSlant->"Italic"]}]], "3"]}], "+", 
    RowBox[{
     FractionBox["1", "24"], 
     SuperscriptBox[
      StyleBox[
       RowBox[{"\[Delta]", 
        StyleBox["r",
         FontSlant->"Italic"]}]], "4"]}], "+"}], 
   "..."}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8105567537363048`*^9, 3.810556892278119*^9}, {
   3.8105570778110213`*^9, 3.810557113786805*^9}, 3.8105573256243377`*^9, {
   3.810557455167451*^9, 3.810557477067909*^9}, {3.8119372649134827`*^9, 
   3.811937320630536*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e408f15e-d3f5-4c42-9ac8-\
736865467c3d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "As we discussed previously, if we truncate at the third term in the \
expansion above (",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox["1", "24"], 
